Can the euro be fixed?
PARIS – German Finance Minister Wolfgang Schäuble recently put the option of Greece exiting the euro on the table, hoping to send a signal that no member state can be exempt from the strict discipline of the monetary union.
In fact, his proposal sparked a wide-ranging discussion about the principles underlying the euro, its governance model, and the very raison d'être for its existence.
Two weeks before Schäuble’s proposal was put forward, European leaders had already noted a report on the future of the euro written by European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker and his colleagues from other EU institutions. But the new debate over Greece has led many policymakers to believe that a return to the original starting point is necessary.
Meanwhile, citizens are questioning why they should share a currency.
Is this meaningful? Can there be consensus on Greece's future?
Currency is like a nation; it needs mythology to be established.
Conventional wisdom holds that the euro was the political price Germany paid to France for reunification.
In fact, Germany's reunification was just the final step in an engineering project to address a long-standing problem that began taking shape in the 1980s.
European governments strongly oppose floating exchange rates, seeing them as incompatible with a single market; yet they are unwilling to maintain a monetary system dominated by the Bundesbank in the long term.
A true European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
In hindsight, German reunification was more of a curse than a blessing.
When exchange rates were locked in 1999, Germany was overvalued and economically struggling; France was undervalued and economically booming.
Over the following decade, imbalances grew between the rising Germany and countries experiencing credit booms due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the global financial crisis in 2008, these conditions became perfect storm fodder.
No one knows what Europe would be like without the euro.
Would the fixed exchange rate regime continue or collapse?
Would the Deutsche Mark overvalue again?
Would countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Would a real estate bubble arise in Spain?
Will there be more or less government reform?
It is impossible to establish a counterfactual baseline to assess the impact of the euro.
But this should not be an excuse for complacency.
Over the past 15 years, the eurozone economy has performed dismally, and its political institutions must bear responsibility for this.
What really matters is whether a common European currency remains important for the future.
This issue is often avoided because the cost of exiting the euro is unimaginable (and would be even higher if the disintegration of the eurozone occurred during a crisis, exacerbating tensions among participating countries).
Moreover, abandoning the euro could unleash dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
But, as Kevin O’Rourke of Oxford University recently pointed out, this view is not sufficient.
Logically, it amounts to suggesting that a couple should stay together because the cost of divorce is too high.
Is the euro still meaningful then?
Initially, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
It was assumed that monetary union would promote economic integration and consolidate Europe's long-term growth.
Instead, trade and investment growth within the eurozone has been lackluster, and growth potential has actually diminished.
This is partly because national governments have not gone further than monetary unification to build the eurozone into an economic superpower, instead trying to retain their remaining powers.
This may make sense politically, but it is economically disastrous: Europe’s vast internal market is one of its main assets, so it must not be squandered in the opportunity to strengthen it.
Secondly, people hope that the euro will become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that few countries meet the necessary legal, market, and policy frameworks).
And according to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has largely been realized.
The euro's international use ranks second only to the US dollar, an achievement that helps Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an irrelevant entity.
Thirdly, it is believed (perhaps naively) that the institutions underlying the euro can improve the overall quality of economic policies, as if Europe’s overall policy level is inherently higher than that of individual countries.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test came: the eurozone overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis while underestimating its financial dimension, resulting in poorer performance compared to the US and the UK.
If the euro is to bring prosperity, further policy reforms must be undertaken.
But agreeing on and implementing a schedule requires broad consensus on the nature of the problems.
And the ongoing debate over the Greek issue illustrates how far Europe is from such consensus: participants have conflicting analyses of the roots of the debt crisis, leading to contradictory solutions.
Richard Cooper of Harvard has observed that early efforts at international public health cooperation were hampered by different patterns of disease transmission among countries.
Countries favor joint action but cannot agree on a unified plan because they disagree on how infectious diseases spread from one country to another.
This is the challenge the eurozone faces today.
Fortunately, this problem is not unsolvable; major reforms like establishing the European Stability Mechanism and launching the banking union have already proven this point.
Inconsistencies have not prevented the ECB from taking decisive action, which shows that institutional governance is indeed important.
But reforms and actions only began recently and were implemented under severe crisis pressure, highlighting the difficulty in reaching consensus.
Europe can no longer afford delay and pretense.
The eurozone countries must establish a consistent agenda for governance and political reforms to transform the monetary union into a engine of prosperity, otherwise they will sink into repetitive debates and crises until citizens lose patience or markets lose confidence.
Clarity is the prerequisite for serious discussion and major reform.
Now, all key players have the obligation to clarify what they consider essential, what they find unacceptable, and what they are willing to exchange for what they want.
